Two mushrooms only, growing on the ground, perhaps on some branchlet buried there. They were just on other side of the trail from the log hosting Observation 130305. I thought they would be the same thing, but microscopy showed big difference.

results.notes:
Growing scattered in a bed of needles and rotten maple leaves.

Cap viscid, covered with removable pellicle. Stem dry, puberulous all over. Stem base in a mass of long white fibrils attached to the substrate.

Odor and taste not recorded.

Spores 7-10 × 4-5 microns. Amyloid reaction not checked. Basidia mostly 2-spored, but 4-spored ones seen too, up to 20 microns long and 7 microns wide, sterigmata up to 5 microns. Cheilocystidia forming a sterile band, ~30 × 6 microns. Hyphae on the cortical layer of the stipe smooth, with caulocystidia. Clamps seen in stipitipellis, not sure about the pileipellis.

Doesn’t seem to fit in any Mycena groups with separable pellicle in Maas Geesteranus.

results.notes:
Pileus 2-7 cm broad, plano-convex, glutinous, light brownish yellow (5C-D6,5), with a slight sulcate margin. Flesh white, unchanging, with mild odor and taste. Lamellae adnexo-emarginate, white, thick, subdistant to close, with even edges. Stipe strict or curved, fibrous-tough, 2.5-4 cm long, 4-10 mm broad, equal with a bulbous base, white, moist, silky fibrillose to fibrillose striate, slightly subsquamulose in some above base.

Some pilei were clearly 2x larger in diameter. Noted by Petersen & Hughes (2010) as possibly the largest in the genus.

results.notes:
Recently I got a book (see the reference below) about Peltigerales in the Iberian Peninsula. In particular, this book describes the existing species of Peltigera. According to it there are 23 species of that genus in the Iberian Peninsula, 14 of which in Portugal. I divided these in two groups, the first from places where I already made observations, and the second group with the remaining. Here they are:
1st group: P. canina, P. collina, P. didactyla, P. horizontalis, P. membranacea, P. neckeri, P. polydactylon, P. praetextata, P. rufescens;
2nd group: P. britanica, P. elisabethe, P. hymenina, P. malacea, P. neopolydactylon.

I went back to this location, which was the first where I observed a Peltigera about two years ago, and take new pictures to the “large carpet” (still existing there) of the Pertigera sp. considered in observation 64685. At the time and from the comparison with other specimens in subsequent observations some doubts appear in relation to its classification. From the potential candidates (which include, according to Jason in a comment to observation 80959, P. membranacea, P. monticola, P. ponojensis and P. pratextata), following the reference, only the last one has a distrubution that includes the location of this observation. The first one, though exist in Portugal has a more northern distribution, and the other two are only reported from Spain.
